{"title_page": "Black Scottish identity", "text_new": "'''Black Scottish identity''' is the objective or subjective state of [[Identity (social science)|perceiving oneself]] as a [[black Scottish person]] and as relating to being black Scottish. The identity has been researched academically, particularly within the arts, as well as social sciences, and has been reported on and discussed in the [[media of Scotland]].\n\n==Background==\nBlack Scottish identity has been researched and reported on within a range of contexts and intersecting dimensions. The identity is usually connected with [[black African]] and [[African Caribbean]] heritage or cultural association in Scotland,<ref>{{cite book|author=Millsom Henry-Waring|title=Moving beyond Otherness: Exploring the Polyvocal Subjectivities of African Caribbean Women across the United Kingdom |date=2004|publisher=[[Hecate (journal)|Hecate]]|edition=Volume 30|quote=At the group interviews, a video on Black Scottish Identity was selected as a focal point for discussions, as it questioned the nature of African Caribbean subjectivities in the UK.}}</ref> and academic research in social sciences has focused on perceptions of competing identities:<ref name=\"liinpaa2018\" />\n<blockquote>To some, it\u2019s obvious that the two are not mutually exclusive. To others, Black Scottish identity is a contradiction in terms: either you\u2019re of this place, [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and therefore [[white people|white]], or Other, [[black people|Black]].</blockquote>\n\nIn scholarly publications with a focus on literary works, the writings of [[Maud Sulter]],<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Jonh Flint|editor2=John Kelly|author=Jessica Homberg-Schramm|title=Bigotry, Football and Scotland|date=2013|publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]|isbn=978-0748670376|quote=The negotiation of a Black Scottish identity will be exemplified on the work of two black Scottish Women poets, namely Jackie Kay and Maud Sulter.}}</ref> and [[Jackie Kay]] in particular, have produced study into the subject in Scotland.<ref>{{cite study|author=Chiara Sestini|title=Being in-between in Jackie Kay\u2019s Trumpet|chapter=Constructing a Black-Scottish identity.|date=2015|publisher=[[University of Padua]]|page=131|quote=Then I discuss how the author constructs Black-Scottish identities in Trumpet and how her Black-Scottish characters are  subjected to racist prejudices.}}</ref><ref>{{cite study|author=Lars Eckstein|title=Performing Jazz, Defying Essence|chapter=Singing with/as the \"other\"|isbn=978-3-8260-3365-0|date=2016|publisher=[[University of Potsdam]]|quote=Author's biography such as the riddles of a black Scottish identity, lesbianism, or the experience of adoption.}}</ref> Kay's work and commentary is preeminent in the potrayal of black Scottishness and identity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michaela Schrage-Fruh|title=Folia litteraria Anglica|chapter=\u201cThe Multiplicity of What I Am\u201d: Black Scottishness in the Poetry of Jackie Kay\"|edition=Volume 8|date=2009|publisher=[[University of \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]|quote=This remark made by Jackie Kay in 2002 vividly illustrates what she has elsewhere referred to as the \u201cinherent contradiction\u201d (Wilson  121) of her Black Scottish identity.}}</ref> Academics, such as professor Alan Rice, have analyzed how the writer's 1998 novel ''[[Trumpet (novel)|Trumpet]]'' harnessed [[African-American music]] and traditions in order to explore black Scottish identity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rice|title=Creating Memorials, Building Identities:  The Politics of Memory in the Black Atlantic|date=2012|publisher=[[Liverpool University Press]]|isbn=978-1846317590|quote=For instance, [[Jackie Kay]]'s novel ''[[Trumpet|Trumpet (novel)]]'' (1998) utilises the resources of the African American musical tradition to tell a story of black Scottish identity.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 2013, Scottish playwright [[David Greig (dramatist)|David Greig]], who was brought up [[Nigeria]], wrote that increased awareness of black Scottish identity was a positive result of the policy and cultural debates ahead of the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bellacaledonia.org.uk/2013/08/04/why-the-debate-on-scottish-independence-might-be-more-interesting-than-you-think/ |title=Why the Debate on Scottish Independence Might Be More Interesting Than You Think|author=David Greig|authorlink=David Greig (dramatist)|quote=Over the last few months I\u2019ve seen [[Scottish independence|Independence]] based discussions on topics as diverse as crowd sourced constitutions, [[peak oil]], [[2008\u20132011 Icelandic financial crisis|Iceland\u2019s collapse]], arts policy in Finland, land reform, wildness as a concept, Black identity in Scotland, the function of defence forces|date=4 August 2014|work=[[Bella Caledonia]]}}</ref>\n\nA 2017 study into [[Somalis in the United Kingdom|Scottish Somalis]] living in [[Glasgow]] detailed how monolithic black identity in Scotland had created cultural identification issues. [[University of Edinburgh]] research-fellow Emma Hill's analysis detailed the potential conflicts created by the idenity and its tendency to exclude the group's religious faith as Muslims.<ref>{{cite study|author=Emma Hill|title=Somali Voices in Glasgow City: Who Speaks?  Who Listens?An Ethnography|date=2017|publisher=[[University of Edinburgh]]|location=[[Heriot-Watt University]]|page=295|chapter=Mapping whiteness, Somali voices and the spaces of Glasgow City|quote=In the meantime, a whiteness-led categorisation of a Somali person as \u2018Black\u2019 would  compound  their  racialised  exclusion  from  [[Islam]]  and  disregard their self-defined racial identity. Under the white gaze in [[Glasgow  City]],  Somali  people were thus subject to \u2018hailings\u2019 that saw them as doubly Other or as partial subjects, and extended the same categorisations  to their occupations of public space.}}</ref> [[Queen Margaret University]]'s Dr Rebecca Finkel, Dr Briony Sharp and Dr Majella Sweeney explored the identity and its ethnocultural expression in Scottish society in their 2018 [[Routledge]] research-series.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Rebecca Finkel|editor2=Briony Sharp|editor3=Majella Sweeney|title=Accessibility, Inclusion, and Diversity in Critical Event Studies|date=2018|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-0815350828}}</ref>\n\n==Academic research==\nThe works of [[Jackie Kay]] have been widely examined in the emergence of a black Scottish identity in the nation.\n<ref>{{cite book|author=Jessica Homberg-Schramm|title=\u2018Colonised by Wankers.\u2019 Postcolonialism in Contemporary Scottish Fiction|date=2018|publisher=[[University of Cologne]]|isbn=978-3946198284|page=109-120|chapter=\"Black Scottish Writing\" - A New Heritage?|quote=[[Jackie Kay|Kay]] is constantly making and re-making that black Scottish identity, creating a [[black Scottish people|black Scottish]] tradition, a space for herself \u201d ([[Carole Seymour-Jones|Jones]] 2004, 200).}}</ref> [[Carole Seymour-Jones]]'s 2009 ''Disappearing Men'', which analyzes Kay's black character (Joss Moody) in ''[[Trumpet (novel)|Trumpet]]'', argues that black Scottish identity is a form of inclusive declaration which defies oversimplified categorisation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Carole Seymour-Jones|authorlink=Carole Seymour-Jones|title=Disappearing Men: Gender Disorientation in Scottish Fiction 1979-1999|date=2009|publisher=[[Rodopi (publisher)|Rodopi]]|isbn=978-9042026988|page=99|chapter=''Between Being: Jackie Kay's'' Trumpet|quote=Doubleness can also describe Joss's racial identity, a black Scottish identity that is a declaration of an inclusive in-betweenness exceeding simple categorisation.}}</ref> [[University of Zadar]] assistant professor, Vesna Uki\u0107 Ko\u0161ta, has written of black Scottish idenity, examining another Kay work (''The Adoption Papers'') and its intersection with parent-child relations.<ref>{{cite book|author=Vesna Uki\u0107 Ko\u0161ta|title=Migrations: Literary and Linguistic Aspects|date=2019|publisher=[[Peter Lang (publisher)]]|location=|isbn=978-363178514-0|page=109-120|chapter=On Mothers, Daughters and Black Scottish Identity in Jackie Kay's 'The Adoption Papers'|quote=}}</ref>\n\nDr Minna Liinp\u00e4\u00e4's 2018 ''Nationalism from Above and Below'', published by the [[University of Glasgow]], examined nationalism and racialised society in Scotland. The thesis, which  studied the experiences of black Scots,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glasgowinternational.org/artists/claire-heuchan/ |title=Artists: Claire Heuchan|quote=As a Blackwoman: On Black Scottish Identity|date=2020|publisher=[[Glasgow International]]}}</ref> analyzed perceptions of contradiction between blackness and Scottishness.<ref name=\"liinpaa2018\">{{cite study|author=Minna Liinp\u00e4\u00e4'|title=Nationalism from Above and Below: Interrogating \u2018race\u2019, \u2018ethnicity\u2019and belonging in post-devolutionary Scotland|chapter=Friendly and Welcoming?: Experiencing Nationalism in Scotland|date=2018|publisher=[[University of Glasgow]]|page=213}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Gerry Hassan]]'s 2019 ''Scotland the Brave? Twenty Years of Change and Devolution'',  [[University of Edinburgh]] professor Dr Nasar Meer explores the political challenges for ethnic minorities, and specifically black Scots, in expressing their Scottish national identity.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Gerry Hassan|author=Nasar Meer|title=Scotland the Brave? Twenty Years of Change and Devolution|date=2019|publisher=Luath Press|isbn=978-1913025021|page=71|chapter=Race Equality and Nationhood|quote=The second is the more nebulous but no less relevant question of national identity, and specifically how this cultivates a certain kind of political environment in which black and ethnic minorities negotiate post-devolution Scotland.}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Scotland topics}}\n{{Immigration from Africa}}\n\n[[Category:African diaspora in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Black British history]]\n[[Category:Black British culture]]\n", "text_old": "'''Black Scottish identity''' is the objective or subjective state of [[Identity (social science)|perceiving oneself]] as a [[black Scottish person]] and as relating to being black Scottish. The identity has been researched academically, particularly within the arts, as well as social sciences, and has been reported on and discussed in the [[media of Scotland]].\n\n==Background==\nBlack Scottish identity has been researched and reported on within a range of contexts and intersecting dimensions. The identity is usually connected with [[black African]] and [[African Caribbean]] heritage or cultural association in Scotland,<ref>{{cite book|author=Millsom Henry-Waring|title=Moving beyond Otherness: Exploring the Polyvocal Subjectivities of African Caribbean Women across the United Kingdom |date=2004|publisher=[[Hecate (journal)|Hecate]]|edition=Volume 30|quote=At the group interviews, a video on Black Scottish Identity was selected as a focal point for discussions, as it questioned the nature of African Caribbean subjectivities in the UK.}}</ref> and academic research in social sciences has focused on perceptions of competing identities:<ref name=\"liinpaa2018\" />\n<blockquote>To some, it\u2019s obvious that the two are not mutually exclusive. To others, Black Scottish identity is a contradiction in terms: either you\u2019re of this place, [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and therefore [[white people|white]], or Other, [[black people|Black]].</blockquote>\n\nIn scholarly publications with a focus on literary works, the writings of [[Maud Sulter]],<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Jonh Flint|editor2=John Kelly|author=Jessica Homberg-Schramm|title=Bigotry, Football and Scotland|date=2013|publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]|isbn=978-0748670376|quote=The negotiation of a Black Scottish identity will be exemplified on the work of two black Scottish Women poets, namely Jackie Kay and Maud Sulter.}}</ref> and [[Jackie Kay]] in particular, have produced study into the subject in Scotland.<ref>{{cite study|author=Chiara Sestini|title=Being in-between in Jackie Kay\u2019s Trumpet|chapter=Constructing a Black-Scottish identity.|date=2015|publisher=[[University of Padua]]|page=131|quote=Then I discuss how the author constructs Black-Scottish identities in Trumpet and how her Black-Scottish characters are  subjected to racist prejudices.}}</ref><ref>{{cite study|author=Lars Eckstein|title=Performing Jazz, Defying Essence|chapter=Singing with/as the \"other\"|isbn=978-3-8260-3365-0|date=2016|publisher=[[University of Potsdam]]|quote=Author's biography such as the riddles of a black Scottish identity, lesbianism, or the experience of adoption.}}</ref> Kay's work and commentary is preeminent in the potrayal of black Scottishness and identity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michaela Schrage-Fruh|title=Folia litteraria Anglica|chapter=\u201cThe Multiplicity of What I Am\u201d: Black Scottishness in the Poetry of Jackie Kay\"|edition=Volume 8|date=2009|publisher=[[University of \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]|quote=This remark made by Jackie Kay in 2002 vividly illustrates what she has elsewhere referred to as the \u201cinherent contradiction\u201d (Wilson  121) of her Black Scottish identity.}}</ref> Academics, such as professor Alan Rice, have analyzed how the writer's 1998 novel ''[[Trumpet (novel)|Trumpet]]'' harnessed [[African-American music]] and traditions in order to explore black Scottish identity.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alan Rice|title=Creating Memorials, Building Identities:  The Politics of Memory in the Black Atlantic|date=2012|publisher=[[Liverpool University Press]]|isbn=978-1846317590|quote=For instance, [[Jackie Kay]]'s novel ''[[Trumpet|Trumpet (novel)]]'' (1998) utilises the resources of the African American musical tradition to tell a story of black Scottish identity.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 2013, Scottish playwright [[David Greig (dramatist)|David Greig]], who was brought up [[Nigeria]], wrote that increased awareness of black Scottish identity was a positive result of the policy and cultural debates ahead of the [[2014 Scottish independence referendum]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bellacaledonia.org.uk/2013/08/04/why-the-debate-on-scottish-independence-might-be-more-interesting-than-you-think/ |title=Why the Debate on Scottish Independence Might Be More Interesting Than You Think|author=David Greig|authorlink=David Greig (dramatist)|quote=Over the last few months I\u2019ve seen [[Scottish independence|Independence]] based discussions on topics as diverse as crowd sourced constitutions, [[peak oil]], [[2008\u20132011 Icelandic financial crisis|Iceland\u2019s collapse]], arts policy in Finland, land reform, wildness as a concept, Black identity in Scotland, the function of defence forces|date=4 August 2014|work=[[Bella Caledonia]]}}</ref>\n\nA 2017 study into [[Somalis in the United Kingdom|Scottish Somalis]] living in [[Glasgow]] detailed how monolithic black identity in Scotland had created cultural identification issues. [[University of Edinburgh]] research-fellow Emma Hill's analysis detailed the potential conflicts created by the idenity and its tendency to exclude the group's religious faith as Muslims.<ref>{{cite study|author=Emma Hill|title=Somali Voices in Glasgow City: Who Speaks?  Who Listens?An Ethnography|date=2017|publisher=[[University of Edinburgh]]|location=[[Heriot-Watt University]]|page=295|chapter=Mapping whiteness, Somali voices and the spaces of Glasgow City|quote=In the meantime, a whiteness-led categorisation of a Somali person as \u2018Black\u2019 would  compound  their  racialised  exclusion  from  [[Islam]]  and  disregard their self-defined racial identity. Under the white gaze in [[Glasgow  City]],  Somali  people were thus subject to \u2018hailings\u2019 that saw them as doubly Other or as partial subjects, and extended the same categorisations  to their occupations of public space.}}</ref> [[Queen Margaret University]]'s Dr Rebecca Finkel, Dr Briony Sharp and Dr Majella Sweeney 2018 [[Routledge]] research-series, explored the identity and its ethnocultural expression in Scottish society.\n<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Rebecca Finkel|editor2=Briony Sharp|editor3=Majella Sweeney|title=Accessibility, Inclusion, and Diversity in Critical Event Studies|date=2018|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-0815350828}}</ref>\n\n==Academic research==\nThe works of [[Jackie Kay]] have been widely examined in the emergence of a black Scottish identity in the nation.\n<ref>{{cite book|author=Jessica Homberg-Schramm|title=\u2018Colonised by Wankers.\u2019 Postcolonialism in Contemporary Scottish Fiction|date=2018|publisher=[[University of Cologne]]|isbn=978-3946198284|page=109-120|chapter=\"Black Scottish Writing\" - A New Heritage?|quote=[[Jackie Kay|Kay]] is constantly making and re-making that black Scottish identity, creating a [[black Scottish people|black Scottish]] tradition, a space for herself \u201d ([[Carole Seymour-Jones|Jones]] 2004, 200).}}</ref> [[Carole Seymour-Jones]]'s 2009 ''Disappearing Men'', which analyzes Kay's black character (Joss Moody) in ''[[Trumpet (novel)|Trumpet]]'', argues that black Scottish identity is a form of inclusive declaration which defies oversimplified categorisation.<ref>{{cite book|author=Carole Seymour-Jones|authorlink=Carole Seymour-Jones|title=Disappearing Men: Gender Disorientation in Scottish Fiction 1979-1999|date=2009|publisher=[[Rodopi (publisher)|Rodopi]]|isbn=978-9042026988|page=99|chapter=''Between Being: Jackie Kay's'' Trumpet|quote=Doubleness can also describe Joss's racial identity, a black Scottish identity that is a declaration of an inclusive in-betweenness exceeding simple categorisation.}}</ref> [[University of Zadar]] assistant professor, Vesna Uki\u0107 Ko\u0161ta, has written of black Scottish idenity, examining another Kay work (''The Adoption Papers'') and its intersection with parent-child relations.<ref>{{cite book|author=Vesna Uki\u0107 Ko\u0161ta|title=Migrations: Literary and Linguistic Aspects|date=2019|publisher=[[Peter Lang (publisher)]]|location=|isbn=978-363178514-0|page=109-120|chapter=On Mothers, Daughters and Black Scottish Identity in Jackie Kay's 'The Adoption Papers'|quote=}}</ref>\n\nDr Minna Liinp\u00e4\u00e4's 2018 ''Nationalism from Above and Below'', published by the [[University of Glasgow]], examined nationalism and racialised society in Scotland. The thesis, which  studied the experiences of black Scots,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://glasgowinternational.org/artists/claire-heuchan/ |title=Artists: Claire Heuchan|quote=As a Blackwoman: On Black Scottish Identity|date=2020|publisher=[[Glasgow International]]}}</ref> analyzed perceptions of contradiction between blackness and Scottishness.<ref name=\"liinpaa2018\">{{cite study|author=Minna Liinp\u00e4\u00e4'|title=Nationalism from Above and Below: Interrogating \u2018race\u2019, \u2018ethnicity\u2019and belonging in post-devolutionary Scotland|chapter=Friendly and Welcoming?: Experiencing Nationalism in Scotland|date=2018|publisher=[[University of Glasgow]]|page=213}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Gerry Hassan]]'s 2019 ''Scotland the Brave? Twenty Years of Change and Devolution'',  [[University of Edinburgh]] professor Dr Nasar Meer explores the political challenges for ethnic minorities, and specifically black Scots, in expressing their Scottish national identity.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Gerry Hassan|author=Nasar Meer|title=Scotland the Brave? Twenty Years of Change and Devolution|date=2019|publisher=Luath Press|isbn=978-1913025021|page=71|chapter=Race Equality and Nationhood|quote=The second is the more nebulous but no less relevant question of national identity, and specifically how this cultivates a certain kind of political environment in which black and ethnic minorities negotiate post-devolution Scotland.}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Scotland topics}}\n{{Immigration from Africa}}\n\n[[Category:A